      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that makes sense. i'm a bit worried about the \"greedy\" part though, like, does that method always work or can it end up making things much worse if you pick a close one early on that leaves you stuck far away at the end? also, any specific way to plan this if some stops have strict time windows?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"greedy\" method you're worried about is a classic trap in logistics, often called the **Greedy Trap**, and yes, it can absolutely leave you stuck in a dead end if you pick the wrong neighbor first.\n\nTo fix this, you need to move from a simple greedy approach to a **2-opt optimization** or a **Local Search** algorithm. This means running the initial greedy run, then systematically swapping segments of the route to see if it creates a shorter loop.\n\nFor strict time windows, the problem shifts from a pure distance minimization to a **Vehicle Routing Problem with Time Windows (VRPTW)**. In this scenario, you can't just pick the nearest stop; you must ensure the vehicle arrives before the deadline and waits if necessary.\n\nThe most robust way to handle this is using a **Constraint Satisfaction Solver** or a specialized heuristic like **Simulated Annealing**. These algorithms don't just look at the immediate next stop; they look at the entire schedule and the constraints (time windows, capacity, distance) to find a globally optimal or near-optimal solution.\n\n**Pro tip:** If you're doing this manually, try the **\"2-opt\" swap** on your current route: take the first",
